# B Theoretical Details
## B. 1 Bond-Dependent Masking Schedule

From Equation (34), we define the continuous-time forward masking probability $1-\alpha_{t}$ at time $t$ with $\alpha_{t}=\exp (-\bar{\sigma}(t))$, where $\bar{\sigma}:[0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{+}$is the cumulative discrete-time masking schedule. Following Lou et al. [114], we apply a log-linear masking schedule $\bar{\sigma}(t)=-\log (1-t)$ for the forward diffusion process which has shown to result in the lowest variance in the NELBO loss [22]. Therefore, the continuous-time probability of remaining unmasked at time $t$ is equal to $\alpha_{t}=\exp \left(-(-\log (1-t))\right)=1-t$ and the weight that scales the negative log loss (NLL) is given by $\frac{1}{t}$ by our derivation in Appendix B.3.
For peptide-bond tokens, we alter the masking schedule such that peptide-bonds are masked at a slower rate at earlier time steps by defining a log-polynomial masking schedule $\bar{\sigma}(t)=-\log \left(1-t^{w}\right)$, for some constant exponent $w>1$. Note that when $w=1$, the log-polynomial schedule reduces to the log-linear schedule. Therefore, the probability of remaining unmasked becomes $\alpha_{t}=(-$ $\left.\left(-\log \left(1-t^{w}\right)\right)\right)=1-t^{w}$ and the weight that scales the negative $\log$ loss (NLL) is given by $\frac{w}{t}$ by our derivation in Appendix B.3.
Since $t \in(0,1]$, the probability that a peptide-bond token remains unmasked at time $t$ is equal to $\alpha_{t}=1-t^{w}$ which is larger than the log-linear schedule for $w>1$. Conversely, the probability that a peptide-bond token is masked before $t$ is $1-\alpha_{t}=t^{w}$ which is smaller than the log-linear schedule for $w>1$. As $t \rightarrow 1, \alpha_{t} \rightarrow 0$ for both the log-linear and log-polynomial time schedules, which means that both peptide-bond and non-peptide bond tokens will have a high probability of being masked in later times in the forward pass diffusion process.
The NLL of the peptide-bond tokens is weighted more heavily than non-peptide bond tokens for $t$ close to 1 . As $t \rightarrow 0$, the NLL weight approaches $\infty$ for all tokens. This biases the reverse diffusion process to unmask peptide bond tokens earlier since it was trained to minimize the loss associated with each unmasking step. As $t \rightarrow 0$, the large NLL weight ensures that the final unmasking steps during the reverse diffusion process result in an unmasked sequence that lies within the space of valid peptide SMILES.

## B. 2 Derivation of Bond-Dependent Reverse Posterior

For a single token, the bond-dependent forward diffusion process is defined by the probability distribution $q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)$ which transforms the clean inputs to sequences with varying degrees of masking

based on a probability distribution $\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)$. We define $\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right): \mathbb{R}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ as a function that takes the clean token encoding $\mathbf{x}_{0}$ and outputs the probability of remaining unmasked at time $t$ depending on whether $\mathbf{x}_{0}$ encodes a peptide bond token.

$$
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)=\operatorname{Cat}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} ;\left(\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}\right)
$$

Then, the marginal forward transition from time $s(n) \rightarrow t(n)$ is defined as

$$
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t(n)} \mid \mathbf{z}_{s(n)}\right)=\operatorname{Cat}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t(n)} ;\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(\mathbf{1}-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\right) \mathbf{m}\right)
$$

In this work, we classify each token into one of two states: peptide-bond tokens and non-peptidebond tokens, which represent amino acid side chains and modifications. We define a function that generates a mask with values of 1 indicating tokens containing or contained within a peptide bond, and 0 otherwise (Algorithm 7). Let $\mathbf{b} \in \mathbb{R}^{|\mathcal{V}|}$ denote a vector with ones at indices of peptide-bond tokens. For derivation purposes, we let $\mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}^{(\ell)}=1$ and $\mathbf{x}_{0}^{(\ell)}=\mathbf{b}$ when a token at position $\ell$ is a peptide bond token. Note that $\mathbf{b}$ is defined differently depending on the context of the token in the full sequence which is handled by the BondMask function. Then, we have $\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)=\left(\mathbf{1}-\mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)(1-t)+\mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\left(1-t^{w}\right)$ or equivalently we can write

$$
\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)= \begin{cases}1-t^{w} & \mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b} \\ 1-t & \mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\end{cases}
$$

By Bayes' rule, the general state-independent form of the true reverse posterior is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) & =\frac{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{z}_{s}\right) q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)} \\
& =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}}{\alpha_{s}}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}}{\alpha_{s}}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}\right]\left[\alpha_{s} \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}\right]}{\left[\alpha_{t} \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}\right]}
\end{aligned}
$$

With bond-dependent masking, the value of $\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)$ and $\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)$ depend on the state of $\mathbf{x}_{0}$, so the bond-dependent reverse posterior becomes

$$
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)=\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}\right]\left[\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}\right]}{\left[\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{t}\right]}
$$

When $\mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{x}_{0}$, the true reverse posterior simplifies to

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)= & \frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\right]\left[\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\right]}{\left[\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\right]} \\
= & \frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\right]\left[\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right]}{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

When $\mathbf{z}_{s} \neq \mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}=0$ so $q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \neq \mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)=0$. When $\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0}$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) & =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{0}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}\right]\left[\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right]}{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)} \\
& =\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\right)\left(\frac{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\right) \\
& =1
\end{aligned}
$$

which means that $\mathbf{z}_{t}$ remains unchanged after unmasking. This supports the carry-over unmasking scheme which explicitly sets the probability of changing an unmasked token equal to $-\infty$.
In the forward diffusion process, a token either remains unchanged or is masked, so the only other case we need to consider is $\mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}$. Since the masking schedule differs only when the ground truth

token is a peptide bond token, or $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}$, we can consider two cases: first, when $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}$ and second, when $\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}$.
Case 1. Consider the case when $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}$ or the ground truth token $\mathbf{x}_{0}$ is a peptide-bond token. From our modified masking schedule, we have $\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})=1-t^{w}$. Therefore, we can write the probability distribution for unmasking a peptide-bond token as

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right) & =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}\right]\left[\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b}) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{s}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{s}\right]}{\left[\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b}) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}\right]} \\
& =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right)\right]\left[\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b}) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{s}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{z}_{s}\right]}{\left(1-\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

The probability of transitioning from a masked state to a peptide-bond token is simplified to

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{b} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right) & =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})}{\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})}\right) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})}{\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})}\right)\right]\left[\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b}) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{b}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{b}\right]}{\left(1-\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})\right)} \\
& =\frac{\left(1-\frac{1-t^{w}}{1-x^{w}}\right)\left(1-s^{w}\right)}{\left(1-\left(1-t^{w}\right)\right)} \\
& =\frac{\left(\frac{1-s^{w}-1+t^{w}}{1-s^{w}}\right)\left(1-s^{w}\right)}{t^{w}} \\
& =\frac{t^{w}-s^{w}}{t^{w}} \\
& =1-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}
\end{aligned}
$$

The probability of remaining in a masked state is

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right) & =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{m})}{\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{m})}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{m})}{\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{m})}\right)\right]\left[\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b}) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}\right]}{\left(1-\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})\right)} \\
& =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{m})}{\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{m})}\right)+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{m})}{\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{m})}\right)\right]\left(1-\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})\right)}{\left(1-\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{b})\right)} \\
& =\frac{1-\alpha_{s}(\mathbf{b})}{1-\alpha_{t}(\mathbf{m})} \\
& =\frac{1-\left(1-s^{w}\right)}{1-\left(1-t^{w}\right)} \\
& =\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}
\end{aligned}
$$

which aligns with the constraint that $\mathbf{z}_{t} \in\left\{\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right\}$ in the forward diffusion process.
Case 2: Consider the case when $\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}$ or the ground truth token $\mathbf{x}_{0}$ is not a peptide-bond token. From the baseline log-linear masking schedule, we have $\vec{\alpha}_{t}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}=1-t$. Therefore, we can write the probability distribution for unmasking a peptide-bond token as

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right) & =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}\right]\left[\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}\right]}{\left[\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right) \mathbf{m}^{\top} \mathbf{m}\right]} \\
& =\frac{\left[\left(\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)}\right)\right]\left[\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right)\right]}{\left[\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right)\right]}
\end{aligned}
$$

With similar steps to Case 1, the probability of transitioning from a masked state to a non-peptide-bond token is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right) & =\frac{\left(1-\frac{\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\right)\left(1-\alpha_{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right)}{\left(1-\alpha_{t}\left(\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\right)} \\
& =\frac{\left(1-\frac{1-t}{1-s}\right)(1-(1-s))}{(1-(1-t))} \\
& =\frac{t-s}{t} \\
& =1-\frac{s}{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

It follows that the probability of remaining in a masked state in the reverse process is

$$
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right)=\frac{s}{t}
$$

This demonstrates that the probability of remaining in a masked state when $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}$ is smaller than when $\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}$ since taking the exponent of a fraction results in a smaller value. So we have $\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}<\frac{s}{t}$ for $w>1$.

Combining Equations (60) and (63) we get the following distribution for the case when $\mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}$ and $\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) & =\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}+\frac{s}{t} \\
& =\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}} \mathbf{b}-\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0} \\
& =\left(\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly, combining (59) and (62) we get the following distribution for the case when $\mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}$ and $\mathbf{z}_{s} \neq \mathbf{m}$ or equivalently $\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) & =\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(1-\frac{s}{t}\right) \\
& =\left(\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{b}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}} \mathbf{b}+\mathbf{1}-\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0} \\
& =\left(\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{t-s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, we can write the true reverse posterior as

$$
q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)= \begin{cases}\left(\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{t-s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0} \mathbf{x}_{0}+\left(\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0} \mathbf{m} & \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m} \\ \mathbf{z}_{t} & \mathbf{z}_{t} \neq \mathbf{m}\end{cases}
$$

Therefore, we get the following expression for the parameterized reverse posterior

$$
p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)= \begin{cases}\left(\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{t-s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right) \mathbf{z}_{s}+\left(\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right) \mathbf{m} & \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m} \\ \mathbf{z}_{t} & \mathbf{z}_{t} \neq \mathbf{m}\end{cases}
$$

# B. 3 Derivation of Bond-Dependent NELBO Loss 

The diffusion objective in its general form is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {NELBO }} & =\sum_{n=1}^{T-1} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t(n)} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[\mathrm{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s(n)} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t(n)}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid\left|p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s(n)} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t(n)}\right)\right)\right]\right. \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{t \in\left\{\frac{1}{T}, \frac{2}{T}, \ldots, 1\right\}} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[T \cdot \mathrm{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid\left|p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right)\right]\right.
\end{aligned}
$$

First, we will derive an expression for the bond-dependent KL-divergence, which measures the difference between the learned reverse posterior $q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right)$ and the true reverse posterior $q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)$ conditioned on the training distribution $\mathbf{x}_{0}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right) \\
& =\sum_{\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{e}_{k}} q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \log \frac{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}\right)} \\
& =\sum_{\mathbf{z}_{s} \in\left\{\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{m}\right\}} q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \log \frac{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}\right)} \\
& =q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \log \frac{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{x}_{0} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}\right)} \\
& +q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \log \frac{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}{p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}=\mathbf{m} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}\right)} \\
& =\left(\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{t-s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0} \log \frac{\left(\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{t-s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}}{\left(\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{t-s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)} \\
& +\left(\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0} \log \frac{\left(\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}}{\left(\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{b}+\frac{s}{t} \mathbf{1}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

In the case where the true token $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}$, we can simplify to

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right) & =\left(\frac{s}{t}-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}+1-\frac{s}{t}\right) \log \frac{\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}+\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}}{\left(\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}-\frac{s}{t}+\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)} \\
& =-\left(1-\frac{s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \log \left(\mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right) \\
& =-\left(\frac{t^{w}-s^{w}}{t^{w}}\right) \log \left(\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Substituting $s=t-\frac{1}{T}$, we can simplify $s^{w}$ to

$$
\begin{aligned}
s^{w} & =\left(t-\frac{1}{T}\right)^{w} \\
& =\left[t\left(1-\frac{1}{t T}\right)\right]^{w} \\
& =t^{w}\left(1-\frac{1}{t T}\right)^{w} \\
& =t^{w}\left(1-\frac{w}{t T}+o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \quad\left((1+x)^{w}=1+w x+o\left(x^{2}\right)\right) \\
& =t^{w}-\frac{w t^{w-1}}{T}+t^{w} o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)$ denotes higher order terms that grow slower than $\frac{1}{T^{2}}$.
Now, we can write

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right) & =-\left(\frac{t^{w}-\left(t^{w}-\frac{w t^{w-1}}{T}+t^{w} o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right)}{t^{w}}\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle \\
& =-\left(\frac{w t^{w-1}}{T}-t^{w} o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle \\
& =-\left(\frac{w}{t T}-o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle
\end{aligned}
$$

In the case where the true token $\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}$, we can simplify to

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right) & =\left(1-\frac{s}{t}\right) \log \frac{\left(1-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{0}}{\left(1-\frac{s}{t}\right) \mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)} \\
& =-\left(1-\frac{s}{t}\right) \log \left(\mathbf{x}_{0}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right) \\
& =-\left(\frac{t-s}{t}\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly, substituting $s=t-\frac{1}{T}$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right) & =-\left(\frac{t-\left(t-\frac{1}{T}\right)}{t}\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle \\
& =-\frac{1}{t T} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, we can combine the two cases using the indicator functions $\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right]$ that evaluates to 1 when $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}$ and 0 otherwise and $\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right]$ that evaluates to 1 when $\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}$ and 0 otherwise. Since this definition of KL divergence is only applicable when $\mathbf{z}_{t}=\mathbf{m}$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right) \\
& =\left[-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right]\left(\frac{w}{t T}-o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right] \frac{1}{t T} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Substituting this back into the equation for the discrete-time diffusion loss, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {NELBO }} & =\mathbb{E}_{t \in\left\{\frac{1}{T}, \frac{2}{T}, \ldots, 1\right\}} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[T \cdot \mathrm{KL}\left(q\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{0}\right) \mid \mid p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right)\right)\right] \\
= & \mathbb{E}_{t \in\left\{\frac{1}{T}, \frac{2}{T}, \ldots, 1\right\}} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)} T \cdot\left[-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right]\left(\frac{w}{t T}-o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right. \\
& \left.-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right] \frac{1}{t T} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right] \\
= & \mathbb{E}_{t \in\left\{\frac{1}{T}, \frac{2}{T}, \ldots, 1\right\}} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right]\left(\frac{w T}{t T}-T o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right. \\
& \left.-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right] \frac{T}{t T} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right] \\
= & \mathbb{E}_{t \in\left\{\frac{1}{T}, \frac{2}{T}, \ldots, 1\right\}} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{z}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right]\left(\frac{w}{t}-T o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right. \\
& \left.-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right] \frac{1}{t} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, taking the limit as $T \rightarrow \infty$, the higher-order term $\lim _{T \rightarrow \infty} T o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)=0$ and we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {NELBO }}^{\infty} & =\lim _{T \rightarrow \infty} \mathcal{L}_{\text {NELBO }} \\
= & \lim _{T \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{E}_{t \in\left\{\frac{1}{T}, \frac{2}{T}, \ldots, 1\right\}} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{x}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right]\left(\frac{w}{t}-T o\left(\frac{1}{T^{2}}\right)\right) \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right. \\
& \left.-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right] \frac{1}{t} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right] \\
= & \mathbb{E}_{t \sim \mathcal{U}(0,1]} \mathbb{E}_{q\left(\mathbf{x}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{b}\right] \frac{w}{t} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right. \\
& \left.-\mathbf{1}\left[\mathbf{x}_{0} \neq \mathbf{b}\right] \frac{1}{t} \log \left\langle\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right\rangle\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

which is the continuous-time NELBO loss for a single token. Therefore, the loss across a sequence of $L$ tokens denoted as $\mathbf{x}_{0}^{(\ell)}$, we have

$$
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{NELBO}}^{=}=\mathbb{E}_{t \sim l(t) 0,1]} \mathbb{E}_{\eta\left(\mathbf{x}_{t} \mid \mathbf{x}_{0}\right)}\left[-\sum_{\ell: \mathbf{x}_{0}^{(\ell)}=\mathbf{b}} \frac{\mathrm{w}}{t} \log \left(\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right)-\sum_{\ell: \mathbf{x}_{0}^{(\ell)} \neq \mathbf{b}} \frac{1}{t} \log \left(\mathbf{x}_{0}, \mathbf{x}_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)\right)\right]
$$

which proves the loss defined in (12).

# B. 4 Gradient Flow of Invalid Loss 

In this section, we show that the penalty for invalid token samples through the argmax function on predicted logits can be effectively backpropagated through the model parameters via our softmax scaling strategy. Here, we will denote the predicted probability for the token $k=\arg \max _{j}\left(\mathbf{x}_{\theta}^{(\ell)} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}, t\right)$ with the highest probability as $x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}$ and all remaining token probabilities as $x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}$ for $j=[1 \ldots \mid \mathcal{V}]$.
First, we define the softmax function as

$$
\operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)=\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}
$$

The partial derivative of the softmax probability $x_{\theta}^{\ell}$ for every token $j$ is given by equation

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}}\left(\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right)=\frac{\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}} \exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)\left(\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)-\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}} \sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)\left(\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)}{\left(\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)^{2}}
$$

Therefore, we have two cases for the derivative: first, the derivative with respect to $x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}$ which denotes the predicted probability for the token that was sampled, and second, the derivative with respect to $x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}$ for $j \neq k$ which denotes the predicted probabilities for all remaining tokens.
For the first case when $j=k$, the partial derivative simplifies to

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}}\left(\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right) & =\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right) \sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)-\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right) \exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\left(\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)^{2}} \\
& =\left(\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right)\left(\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)-\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right) \\
& =\operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)\left(1-\operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

For all $j \neq k$, the derivative simplifies to

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}}\left(\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{K} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right) & =\frac{0-\exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right) \exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\left(\sum_{j=1}^{K} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)^{2}} \\
& =-\left(\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right)\left(\frac{\exp \left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{|\mathcal{V}|} \exp \left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right)}\right) \\
& =-\operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right) \operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The parameters $\theta$ are updated such that the predicted probability of sampling the token $\ell$ with argmax probability $x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}$ which resulted in an invalid peptide SMILES sample is reduced. The gradient update is minimized for predicted probabilities near 0 and 1 , suggesting that the loss function pushes the model towards higher confidence predictions from uncertain predictions to minimize invalid sampling.

$$
x_{\theta, k}^{\prime(\ell)} \leftarrow x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}-\eta \cdot \operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)\left(1-\operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)\right)
$$

where $\eta$ is the learning rate.
In contrast, the parameters of the remaining tokens $x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}$ are updated so that the predicted probability of sampling the other tokens increases proportionally to their original softmax probabilities. This prevents extreme changes in the predicted probabilities of the remaining tokens and ensures that the token distribution remains relatively consistent with the previous iteration.

$$
x_{\theta, j}^{\prime(\ell)} \leftarrow x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}+\eta \cdot \operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, j}^{(\ell)}\right) \operatorname{SM}\left(x_{\theta, k}^{(\ell)}\right)
$$

Here, we show our invalid loss effectively updates parameters to reduce the position-specific token probabilities that result in invalid sequence samplings and push the model predictions toward other high-likelihood tokens.

## C. 5 Evaluation Metrics

Validity is defined as the fraction of peptide SMILES that pass our SMILES2PEPTIDE filter (Algorithm 8), indicating that it translates to a synthesizable peptide.
Uniqueness is defined as the fraction of mutually distinct peptide SMILES.
Diversity is defined as one minus the average Tanimoto similarity between the Morgan fingerprints of every pair of generated sequences, which measures the similarity in structure across generated peptides.

$$
\text { Diversity }=1-\frac{1}{\binom{N_{\text {repeated }}}{2}} \sum_{i, j} \frac{\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right) \cdot \mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{j}\right)}{\left|\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\right|+\left|\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{j}\right)\right|-\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right) \cdot \mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{j}\right)}
$$

where $\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)$ and $\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{j}\right)$ are the 2048-dimensional Morgan fingerprint with radius 3 for a pair of generated sequences $\mathbf{x}_{i}$ and $\mathbf{x}_{j}$.

Similarity to Nearest Neighbor (SNN) is defined as the maximum Tanimoto similarity between a generated sequence $\mathbf{x}_{i}$ with a sequence in the dataset $\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_{j}$.

$$
\mathrm{SNN}=\max _{j \in|\mathcal{D}|}\left(\frac{\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right) \cdot \mathbf{f}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_{j}\right)}{\left|\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\right|+\left|\mathbf{f}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_{j}\right)\right|-\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}\right) \cdot \mathbf{f}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_{j}\right)}\right)
$$

Randomness is defined as the Shannon Entropy [108] on tokenized sequences given as:

$$
E=-\sum_{i}^{L} p_{i} \log _{2}\left(p_{i}\right)
$$

where $p_{i}$ is the probability of $i$-th unique token divided by the total number of tokens $L$ in the sequence.
KL-Divergence is defined as the divergence between the token distribution in the generated peptide SMILES $p_{i}$ and the token distribution in the training data.

$$
\mathrm{KL}(P||Q)=\sum_{i \in V} \int \begin{cases}p_{i} \log _{2}\left(\frac{p_{i}}{q_{i}}\right) & \text { if } q_{i}>0 \\ p_{i} \log _{2}\left(\frac{p_{i}}{10, q}\right) & \text { if } q_{i}=0\end{cases}
$$

where $p_{i}$ is the probability of token $i$ in the training data, and $q_{i}$ is the probability of token $i$ in the generated data.

# D Further Experiments
## D. 1 Case Study for Time-Dependent Multi-Objective Guidance

Some properties of peptides require more intense guidance towards specific structural or sub-structural features, while others may only require small changes in the side chain composition or non-natural modifications. To enable the prioritization of properties during guidance, we introduce a timedependent multi-objective guidance strategy that guides the generation based on only a subset of properties depending on the current iteration number of the MCTS search. To achieve this, we define a $K$-dimensional vector $\mathbf{i}=\left[i_{1}, i_{2}, \ldots, i_{K}\right]$ where each $i_{k}$ is the iteration number to begin guidance for the $k$ th objective. Properties where $i_{k}=0$ are used to guide all iterations, whereas properties where $i_{k}>1$ are used to guide only the iterations from $i_{k} \rightarrow N_{\text {iter }}$.
Our time-dependent guidance operates as follows. During the expansion and rollout steps on iteration $i$, the rolled-out child sequences $\mathbf{x}_{s, i}$ that are non-dominated across the sub-vector of property scores $\mathbf{s}_{i}=\left[s_{k} \mid i_{k} \leq i \leq N_{\text {iter }}\right]$ dependent on the iteration $i$ is added to the Pareto-optimal set $\mathcal{P}^{*}$. Therefore, $\mathbf{x}_{s}$ does not need to be non-dominated in the properties $k$ where $i_{k}>i$. Similarly, only the sequences $\mathbf{x}^{*} \in \mathcal{P}^{*}$ that become dominated when adding $\mathbf{x}_{s}$ in the subset of properties represented in $\mathbf{s}_{i}\left(\mathbf{x}^{*}\right)$ are removed from $\mathcal{P}^{*}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{P}^{\prime *}=\mathcal{P}^{*} \cup\left\{\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}, \mathbf{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right)\right) \mid \forall \mathbf{x}^{*} \in \mathcal{P}^{*} \quad \mathbf{s}_{i}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right) \succeq \mathbf{s}_{i}\left(\mathbf{x}^{*}\right)\right\} \\
& \mathcal{P}^{\prime *}=\mathcal{P}^{*} \backslash\left\{\mathbf{x}^{*} \mid \exists \mathbf{x}_{s} \in \text { children }\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}\right) \text { s.t. } \mathbf{s}_{i}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right) \succ \mathbf{s}_{i}\left(\mathbf{x}^{*}\right)\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

Then, during selection, we only consider the cumulative rewards $\mathbf{W}_{i}=\left[W_{k} \mid i_{k} \leq i \leq N_{\text {iter }}\right]$ for the properties where $i_{k}$ s.t. $i_{k} \leq i \leq N_{\text {iter }}$ when computing the selection score vector $\mathbf{U}_{i}$ to form the Pareto-optimal selection set.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{\prime *}=\mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*} \cup\left\{\mathbf{z}_{s} \mid \forall \mathbf{x}^{*} \in \mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*} \mathbf{U}_{i}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{z}_{s}\right) \succeq \mathbf{U}_{i}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{z}^{*}\right)\right\} \\
& \mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{\prime *}=\mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*} \backslash\left\{\mathbf{z}^{*} \mid \exists \mathbf{z}_{s} \in \text { children }\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}\right) \text { s.t. } \mathbf{U}_{i}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{z}_{s}\right)>\mathbf{U}_{i}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{z}^{*}\right)\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, we select the next node $\mathbf{z}_{s} \sim \mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{\prime *}$ uniformly at random from the Pareto-optimal selection set.
To test this strategy, we generated 100 peptides conditioned only on membrane permeability for the first 50 iterations since we found it as the most challenging property to optimize. Then we conditioned all properties including membrane permeability, binding affinity to GFAP, solubility, hemolysis, and non-fouling. We show that during the first 50 iterations, all properties except membrane permeability show relatively constant average scores, whereas the permeability score increased (Figure 16). Then,

# D. 2 Ablation Studies 

In this section, we report the performance of our multi-objective MCTS-guided discrete diffusion model over different hyperparameter settings. Specifically, we discuss the effects of changing the number of expanded children nodes, the number of iterations, and the tokenization scheme.
Number of Children. The number of children $M$ is the hyperparameter that determines the batch size during the expansion step of MCTS. A small number of expanded nodes would limit the degree of exploration and number of generated sequences for evaluation at each iteration. If the initial iterations resulted in sub-optimal unmasking steps for all children, this could prevent the algorithm from discovering a local or global optimum across objectives. Suppose the number of children is too large. In that case, this can result in a lack of diversity if several sequences from the same expansion step are added to the Pareto-optimal set given their sequence similarity, leading to similar property scores. A large $M$ also slows down runtime significantly. To determine a value for $M$ within the two extremes, we evaluated the performance of the MCTS search for $M=10,50,70,100$. Overall, we found that $M=50$ yields consistently increasing scores across all properties, which we use for the remainder of the study.
Number of Iterations. The number of iterations $N_{\text {iter }}$ determines the number of selection, expansion, rollout, and backpropagation loops executed in a single MCTS run. In addition, $N_{\text {iter }}$ is the maximum value of $t$ or the number of unmasking steps that can be executed before the rollout begins, which corresponds to the maximum tree depth. We found that equating the number of diffusion steps $T$ to the number of MCTS iterations $N_{\text {iter }}$ results in convergence on the property prediction scores as the selection process becomes biased towards a single unmasking scheme. As shown in Figure 6, all property scores converge for $N_{\text {iter }}=T=128$, which we use for the remainder of the study.

Tokenization Scheme. To evaluate the effect of different tokenization methods on the generation quality, we experimented with three different tokenization schemes: SMILES Pair Encoding (SPE) tokenization with the trained vocabulary used by PeptideCLM and Atom Pair Encoding (APE) tokenization for SMILES and SELFIES [99] representations. Overall, we found that the SPE tokenization scheme decreased perplexity and maintained precision while capturing common peptide motifs like bonds and recurring side chains.

return children $\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}\right)$
end procedure

Algorithm 5 Selection
Inputs: Masked root node $\mathbf{z}_{t(T)}$
Output: Expandable leaf node $\mathbf{z}_{t}$
procedure SELECT
while True do
if $\mathbf{z}_{t}$ is non-leaf node and $t \neq 0$ then $\mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*} \leftarrow\{ \} \quad \triangleright$ initialize Pareto front of select scores
for $\mathbf{z}_{s, i}$ in children $\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}\right)$ do
if $\mathbf{z}_{s, i}$ is non-leaf or expandable leaf node then

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbf{U}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{z}_{s, i}\right) \leftarrow \frac{\mathbf{W}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s, i}\right)}{N_{\text {run }}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s, i}\right)}+c \cdot p_{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s, i} \mid \mathbf{z}_{t}\right) \cdot \frac{\sqrt{N_{\text {run }}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}\right)}}{1+N_{\text {run }}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s, i}\right)} \\
& \mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*} \leftarrow \text { UpdateParetoFront }\left(\mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*},\left(\mathbf{z}_{s, i}, \mathbf{U}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}, \mathbf{z}_{s, i}\right)\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

end if
end for
$\triangleright$ set parent node for next iteration as a child node selected uniformly at random from Pareto-optimal set
$\mathbf{z}_{t} \sim \mathcal{P}_{\text {select }}^{*}$
$\operatorname{SELECT}\left(\mathbf{z}_{t}\right) \quad \triangleright$ recursively call select until leaf node is reached else if $t=0$ then $\triangleright$ node is already fully unmasked
$\operatorname{SELECT}\left(\mathbf{z}_{T}\right) \quad \triangleright$ restart selection process from root node
else
return $\mathbf{z}_{t}$
end if
end while
end procedure

# Algorithm 6 Update Pareto Front 

Inputs: Current Pareto-front sequences and score vectors $\mathcal{P}^{*}=\left\{\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}^{*}, \mathbf{s}_{i}^{*}\right)\right\}$, newly sampled sequence and score vector $\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}, \mathbf{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right)\right)$
Output: Reward vector $\mathbf{r}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)$ and updated Pareto-optimal set $\mathcal{P}^{*}$
procedure UpdateParetoFront
if $\mathcal{P}^{*}$ is empty then
$\mathcal{P}^{*} \cdot \operatorname{append}\left(\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}, \mathbf{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right)\right)\right)$
$\mathbf{r}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right) \leftarrow \mathbf{1}^{K} \quad \triangleright$ set reward vector to ones
else
$\triangleright$ vector of boolean flags indicating which sequences are nondominant to x nondominateFlag $\leftarrow$ new bool $\left[\left[\mathcal{P}^{*}\right]\right]$
toDelete $\leftarrow\{ \}$
$\mathbf{r}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right) \leftarrow \mathbf{0}^{K} \quad \triangleright$ set reward vector to zeroes
for $\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}^{*}, \mathbf{s}_{i}^{*}\right)$ in $\mathcal{P}^{*}$ do
$\triangleright$ define vector with 1 where $\mathrm{x}_{s}$ is non-dominated in the property
$\mathbf{n} \leftarrow\left[n_{k}=1\right.$ if $\left.s_{k}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right) \succeq s_{k, i}^{*}\right]$
$\triangleright$ define vector with 1 where $\mathrm{x}_{s, i}$ is dominant in the property
$\mathbf{d} \leftarrow\left[d_{k}=1\right.$ if $\left.s_{k}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right) \succeq s_{k}^{*}\right]$
$\mathbf{r}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s, i}\right) \leftarrow \mathbf{r}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right)+\mathbf{n} \quad \triangleright$ update reward vector
if $\left(\forall n_{k} \in \mathbf{n}\right.$ s.t. $\left.n_{k}=1\right) \wedge\left(\exists d_{k} \in \mathbf{d}\right.$ s.t. $\left.d_{k}=1\right)$ then $\triangleright \mathrm{x}$ dominates $\mathrm{x}^{*}$ toDelete.append( $\left.\mathbf{x}^{*}\right)$
nondominateFlag $[i] \leftarrow$ True
else if $\forall n_{k} \in \mathbf{n}$ s.t. $n_{k}=1$ then $\triangleright \mathrm{x}$ is not dominated by $\mathrm{x}^{*}$ nondominateFlag $[i] \leftarrow$ True
else
nondominateFlag $[i] \leftarrow$ False
end if
end for
$\triangleright$ if $\mathrm{x}_{s}$ is either dominant or non-dominated by all $\mathrm{x}^{*}$ in Pareto-optimal set $\mathcal{P}^{*}$, then add to $\mathcal{P}^{*}$
if $\forall i$ nondominateFlag $[i]=$ True then
$\mathcal{P}^{*} \cdot \operatorname{append}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}, \mathbf{s}\left(\mathbf{x}_{s}\right)\right)$
end if
for x in toDelete do
$\mathcal{P}^{*}$. delete $\left(\mathbf{x}^{*}, \mathbf{s}^{*}\right)$
end for
end if $\quad \triangleright$ return reward vector and updated Pareto-optimal set
return $\mathbf{r}\left(\mathbf{z}_{s}\right), \mathcal{P}^{*}$
end procedure

# Algorithm 7 Bond Mask 

Inputs: List of peptide SMILES strings smiles_list
Output: Position-wise bond mask for each sequence with 1 in positions of peptide bonds and 0 otherwise mask
procedure BONDMASK
bond_patterns $\leftarrow\left[\left(r^{\prime} O C(=0)^{\prime}, '\right.$ ester $^{\prime}$ ),
$\left(r^{\prime} N(C) C(=0)^{\prime}, ' n \_ \text {methyl' }\right)$,
$\left(r^{\prime} C(=0) N(C)^{\prime}, ' n \_ \text {methyl' }\right)$,
$\left(r^{\prime} N[12] C(=0)^{\prime},{ }^{\prime} \text { peptide' }\right)$,
$\left(r^{\prime} C(=0) N[12] ?^{\prime},{ }^{\prime} \text { peptide' }\right)$ ]
for batch_idx, smiles in enumerate(smiles_list) do
positions $\leftarrow$ empty_list()
$\triangleright$ list to store bond positions
used $\leftarrow$ empty_set()
$\triangleright$ set to track used positions
for pattern, bond_type in bond_patterns do
$\triangleright$ identify bonds using patterns
for match in re.finditer(pattern, smiles) do
if not any( $p \in$ range(match.start(), match. end()) for $p$ in used) then positions.append(\{start: match.start(), end: match.end(), type: bond_type, pattern: match.group()\})
used.update(range(match.start(), match.end()))
end if
end for
end for
for pos in positions do $\quad \triangleright$ update the mask for the current SMILES
mask[batch_idx, pos[start]:pos[end]] $\leftarrow 1$
end for
end for
return mask
end procedure

# Algorithm 8 SMILES2PEPTIDE 

Inputs: SMILES String $s$
Output: Batch of $M$ sequences at time $s$.
procedure ANALYZER
if $s$ is correct SMILES format then,
if $s$ contains peptide bond $[\mathrm{NC}(=\mathrm{O})]$ or N -methylated peptide bond $[\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{C}) \mathrm{C}(=\mathrm{O})]$ then,

bond_after: next_pos['pattern'] )

if positions $[-1]$ ['end'] < len(smiles) then, $\quad \triangleright$ last segment segments.append\{ content: smiles[positions [-1] ['end']:], bond_after: positions [-1] ['pattern'] )
end if
end for
end for

abstract:
Peptide therapeutics, a major class of medicines, have achieved remarkable
success across diseases such as diabetes and cancer, with landmark examples
such as GLP-1 receptor agonists revolutionizing the treatment of type-2
diabetes and obesity. Despite their success, designing peptides that satisfy
multiple conflicting objectives, such as target binding affinity, solubility,
and membrane permeability, remains a major challenge. Classical drug
development and structure-based design are ineffective for such tasks, as they
fail to optimize global functional properties critical for therapeutic
efficacy. Existing generative frameworks are largely limited to continuous
spaces, unconditioned outputs, or single-objective guidance, making them
unsuitable for discrete sequence optimization across multiple properties. To
address this, we present PepTune, a multi-objective discrete diffusion model
for the simultaneous generation and optimization of therapeutic peptide SMILES.
Built on the Masked Discrete Language Model (MDLM) framework, PepTune ensures
valid peptide structures with state-dependent masking schedules and
penalty-based objectives. To guide the diffusion process, we propose a Monte
Carlo Tree Search (MCTS)-based strategy that balances exploration and
exploitation to iteratively refine Pareto-optimal sequences. MCTS integrates
classifier-based rewards with search-tree expansion, overcoming gradient
estimation challenges and data sparsity inherent to discrete spaces. Using
PepTune, we generate diverse, chemically-modified peptides optimized for
multiple therapeutic properties, including target binding affinity, membrane
permeability, solubility, hemolysis, and non-fouling characteristics on various
disease-relevant targets. In total, our results demonstrate that MCTS-guided
discrete diffusion is a powerful and modular approach for multi-objective
sequence design in discrete state spaces.
